| last3 = Ando| first3 = Tatsuro| last4 = Harrison| first4 = G.L. \"Abby| last5 = Fordyce| first5 = R. Ewan| last6 = Arnason| first6 = Ulfur| last7 = Penny| first7 = David| year = 2006| title = Early Penguin Fossils, plus Mitochondrial Genomes, Calibrate Avian Evolution| journal = [[Molecular Biology and Evolution]]| volume = 23| issue = 6| pages = 1144\u20131155| pmid =  16533822| pmc = | url = http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/reprint/23/6/1144| ref = harv\n}}  [http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/full/msj124/DC1 Supplementary Material] {{open access}}       <!-- {{sfn|Slack|Jones|Ando|Harrison|2006}}-->\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Caloenas nicobarica}}\n{{Wikispecies|Caloenas nicobarica}}\n* [http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/nicobar-pigeon-caloenas-nicobarica Nicobar Pigeon media] at the Internet Bird Collection\n\n{{Birds|state=collapsed}}\n{{portalbar|Birds|Animals|Biology}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q605804}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:pigeon, Nicobar}}\n[[Category:Caloenas|Nicobar pigeon]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Andaman and Nicobar Islands]]\n[[Category:Birds of Malesia]]\n[[Category:Birds of Palau]]\n[[Category:Birds of Melanesia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|Nicobar pigeon]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of bird}}\n{{speciesbox\n | image = Nicobar Pigeon 820.jpg\n | status = NT\n | status_system = IUCN3.1\n | status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22690974/0 |title=''Caloenas nicobarica'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n | genus  = Caloenas\n | species  = nicobarica\n | authority  = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n | synonyms = ''Columba nicobarica'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Nicobar pigeon''' (''Caloenas nicobarica'', [[Car language|Car]]: ''{{lang|caq|ma-k\u016b\u00f6-k\u00f6}}''<ref>Whitehead, Rev. G.; ''Dictionary of the Car (Nicobarese) language''; published 1925 by American Baptist Mission Press; pp. ''xxvi''-''xxxii''</ref>) is found on small islands and in coastal regions from the [[Andaman and Nicobar Islands]], [[India]], east through the [[Malay Archipelago]], to the [[Solomon Islands|Solomons]] and [[Palau]]. It is the only living member of the genus ''[[Caloenas]]'' and may be the closest living relative of the extinct [[dodo]], and the extinct [[Rodrigues solitaire]].\n\n==Taxonomy==\nIn 1738 the English naturalist [[Eleazar Albin]] included a description and two illustrations of the Nicobar pigeon in his ''A Natural History of Birds''. When in 1758 the Swedish naturalist [[Carl Linnaeus]] updated his ''[[Systema Naturae]]'' for the [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|tenth edition]], he placed the Nicobar pigeon with all the other pigeons in the [[genus]] ''[[Columba (genus)|Columba]]''. Linnaeus included a brief description, coined the [[binomial name]] ''Columba nicobarica'' and cited Albin's work.<ref>{{cite book | last=Linnaeus | first=Carl | authorlink=Carl Linnaeus | year=1758 | title= Systema Naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis | volume= Volume 1 | edition=10th | page=164 | publisher=Holmiae:Laurentii Salvii | language=Latin | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/727071 }}</ref> The species is now placed in the genus ''[[Caloenas]]'' that was introduced by the English zoologist [[George Robert Gray]] in 1840 with the Nicobar pigeon as the [[type species]].<ref>{{ cite book | last=Gray | first=George Robert | author-link=George Robert Gray | year=1840 | title=A List of the Genera of Birds : with an Indication of the Typical Species of Each Genus | place=London | publisher=R. and J.E. Taylor | page=59 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/13668976 }}</ref><ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | editor3-last=Rasmussen | editor3-first=Pamela | editor3-link=Pamela Rasmussen | year=2020 | title=Pigeons | work=IOC World Bird List Version 10.1 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/pigeons/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=21 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nTwo [[subspecies]] are recognised:<ref name=ioc/>\n* ''C. n. nicobarica'' ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], 1758) \u2013 [[Andaman Islands|Andaman]] and [[Nicobar Islands]], [[Malay Archipelago]] to New Guinea, Philippines and [[Solomon Islands]]\n* ''C. n. pelewensis'' [[Otto Finsch|Finsch]], 1875 \u2013 [[Palau|Palau Island]]\n\nBased on [[cladistic]] analysis of [[mtDNA]] [[cytochrome b|cytochrome ''b'']] and 12S [[rRNA]] [[DNA sequence|sequences]], the Nicobar pigeon is sometimes called the closest living relative of the [[extinct]] [[didine]]s (Raphinae), which include the famous [[dodo]] (''Raphus cucullatus'').{{Sfn|Shapiro et al.|2002}} However, the study's results showed this as one weak possibility from a limited sample of [[taxa]]. <!-- In addition, the [[passenger pigeon]] (of which [[ancient DNA]] was also sequenced) turns up in a somewhat implausible position&nbsp;\u2013 close to the [[cuckoo-dove]]s (''Macropygia''), in a largely [[Old World]] radiation&nbsp;\u2013 questioning the accuracy of the proposed DNA sequence of the dodo (though not of the [[Rodrigues solitaire]] (''Pezophaps solitaria'') which was independently verified). [refuted] --> In any case, [[nDNA]] [[\u03b2-fibrinogen]] [[intron]] 7 sequence data agrees with the idea of the Raphinae as a [[subfamily]] of pigeons (and not an independent family, as was previously believed due to their bizarre [[apomorph]]ies) that was part of a diverse [[Indopacific]] [[evolutionary radiation|radiation]], to which the Nicobar pigeon also belongs.{{sfnm|1a1=Johnson|1a2=Clayton|1y=2000|2a1=Shapiro et al.|2y=2002}}\n\nThe following [[cladogram]], from Shapiro and colleagues (2002), shows the Nicobar pigeon's closest relationships within Columbidae, a [[clade]] consisting of generally ground-dwelling island endemics.{{sfn|Shapiro et al.|2002}}\n\n{{clade | style = font-size: 90%;\n|1={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n      |1=''Goura victoria'' ([[Victoria crowned pigeon]])\n      |2={{clade\n         |1={{clade\n            |1={{clade\n               |1=''Caloenas nicobarica'' (Nicobar pigeon)\n               |2={{clade\n                  |1=''Pezophaps solitaria'' ([[Rodrigues solitaire]])\n                  |2=''Raphus cucullatus'' ([[dodo]])\n                  }}\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   |2=''Didunculus strigirostris'' ([[tooth-billed pigeon]])\n   }}\n}}\n\n[[File:CaloenasNicobaricaBaker.jpg|thumb|left|Painting by [[Henrik Gr\u00f6nvold]]]]\nA similar cladogram was published in 2007, differing only in the inverted placement of ''Goura'' and ''Didunculus'', as well as in the inclusion of the [[pheasant pigeon]] and the [[thick-billed ground pigeon]] at the base of the clade.{{sfn|Pereira et al.|2007}}\n\n''C. nicobarica'' is a quite singular [[Columbiformes|columbiform]] (though less [[autapomorph]]ic than the [[flightless bird|flightless]] Raphinae), as are for example the [[tooth-billed pigeon]] (''Didunculus strigirostris'') and the [[crowned pigeon]]s (''Goura''), which are typically considered distinct subfamilies. Hence, the Nicobar pigeon may well constitute another now-[[monotypic]] subfamily. And while any of the semi-[[Terrestrial animal|terrestrial]] pigeons of [[Southeast Asia]] and the [[Wallacea]] cannot be excluded as possible closest living relative of the Raphinae, the Nicobar pigeon makes a more plausible candidate than for example the group of [[imperial-pigeon]]s and [[fruit-dove]]s, which seems to be part of the same radiation.{{sfnm|1a1=Johnson|1a2=Clayton|1y=2000|2a1=Shapiro et al.|2y=2002}}\n\nWhether it is possible to clarify such deep-time [[phylogenies]] without a comprehensive study of all major lineages of living [[Columbidae]] remains to be seen. The primitive [[molecular clock]] used to infer the date the ancestors of the Nicobar pigeon and the didines diverged has since turned out to be both unreliable and [[calibration|miscalibrated]]. But what little evidence is available still suggests that the Nicobar pigeon is distinct from all other living lifeforms since the [[Paleogene]]&nbsp;\u2013 most likely some time between 56-34 [[million years ago]] during the [[Eocene]], which makes up the bulk of the Paleogene [[Geologic period|period]].{{sfnm|1a1=Johnson|1a2=Clayton|1y=2000|2a1=Shapiro et al.|2y=2002|3a1=Slack|3a2=Jones|3a3=Ando|3a4=Harrison|3y=2006}}\n\nFrom [[subfossil]] bones found on [[New Caledonia]] and [[Tonga]], an [[extinct]] species of ''Caloenas'', the [[Kanaka pigeon]] (''[[Caloenas canacorum|C. canacorum]]'') was described. It was about one-quarter larger<ref>{{Cite journal|title=The mysterious Spotted Green Pigeon and its relation to the Dodo and its kindred|last=Tim H. Heupink, Hein van Grouw, David M. Lambert|date=July 2014|pmc=4099497|pmid=25027719|doi=10.1186/1471-2148-14-136|volume=14|journal=BMC Evol Biol|page=136}}</ref><!-- longer or heavier? --> than the Nicobar pigeon. Considering that it must have been a good source of food, it was most likely hunted to extinction by the first human settlers of its home islands. It probably was extinct by 500 BC. The [[Spotted green pigeon]] (''C. maculata'') is a more recently extinct species from an unknown [[Pacific]] locality; it probably disappeared in the 19th century and most likely succumbed to introduced [[Europe]]an [[rat]]s. It is placed in ''Caloenas'' as the least awkward possibility; its true affinities are presently indeterminate and it is perhaps more likely to represent a distinct genus of the Indopacific radiation of Columbidae.<ref>Fuller (2000): p. 174\u2013175.</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Nicobar Pigeon.jpg|thumb|left|An adult at the [[Milwaukee County Zoological Gardens]] with iridescent scapulars]]\n\nIt is a large pigeon, measuring {{convert|40|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length. The head is grey, like the upper neck plumage, which turns into green and copper hackles. The tail is very short and pure white. The rest of its plumage is metallic green. The [[cere]] of the dark bill forms a small blackish knob; the strong legs and feet are dull red. The [[Iris (anatomy)|irides]] are dark.<ref name=\"grimmettetal1999\">Grimmett et al. (2009).</ref>\n\nFemales are slightly smaller than males; they have a smaller bill knob, shorter hackles and browner underparts. Immature birds have a black tail and lack almost all [[iridescence]]. There is hardly any variation across the birds' wide range. Even the Palau [[subspecies]] ''C. n. pelewensis'' has merely shorter neck hackles, but is otherwise almost identical.<ref name=\"grimmettetal1999\" />\n\nIt is a very vocal species, giving a low-pitched repetitive call.<ref name=\"grimmettetal1999\" />\n==Distribution and habitat==\n[[File:Head of Nicobar Pigeon.jpg|thumb|Close up of the head]]\n\nOn the [[Nicobar Islands]] (which are referred to in its [[common name|common]] and [[scientific name]]s), the most significant colony in our time was found on [[Batti Malv]], a remote [[wildlife sanctuary]] between [[Car Nicobar]] and [[Teressa (Nicobar Islands)|Teressa]]. The [[2004 Indian Ocean tsunami]] caused massive damage on the Nicobar Islands, and it is still not quite clear to what extent Batti Malv was affected. But while everything on some islets in the [[Great Nicobar Biosphere Reserve]] was destroyed, Batti Malv [[lighthouse]]&nbsp;\u2013 a [[skeletal tower]] a dozen metres high, standing a few metres [[Above mean sea level|ASL]] at the highest point of the low-lying island&nbsp;\u2013 was little-damaged and put back in operation by the [[survey ship]] [[INS Sandhayak|INS ''Sandhayak'']] less than one month after the disaster. An April 2007 survey by the [[Indian Coast Guard]] vessel [[ICGS Vikram|ICGS ''Vikram'']] found the lighthouse tower \"totally covered\" in [[vine]]s, indicating rampant regeneration of vegetation&nbsp;\u2013 but perhaps also that damage to the island's forest was severe, as a cover of creeping plants is typical of early [[Ecological succession|succession]] stages, while a photo of the lighthouse taken before the tsunami shows rather mature forest.<ref>Sankaran (1998), IHMDN (2005), ICG (2007), [[#{{sfnRef|Rowlett|2008}}|Rowlett (2008)]].</ref>\n\n===Found in Australia===\nA Nicobar pigeon was found by the [[Bardi Jawi]] [[Indigenous rangers]] on the [[Dampier Peninsula]] in the western Kimberley, [[Australia]] in May 2017. As part of [[biosecurity]] measures, it was reported to [[quarantine]] services was removed by Australian Department of Agriculture officials.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.klc.org.au/bardi-jawi-rangers-discover-nicobar-pigeon|website=Kimberley Land Council|title=Bardi Jawi rangers discover Nicobar pigeon|date= 5 May 2017|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|website=ABC News|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-05/dodo-relative-nicobar-pigeon-found-in-north-west-australia/8500442|title=Dodo's relative, Nicobar pigeon, found in north-west Australia's Kimberley region|first1=Ben|last1=Collins|first2=Vanessa|last2= Mills|date= 5 May 2017|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=The Guardian|title=Pigeon related to dodo found on Australian mainland for first time|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/may/05/pigeon-related-to-dodo-found-on-australian-mainland-for-first-time|first=Calla|last=Wahlquist|date= 5 May 2017|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\nThe Nicobar pigeon's breeding range encompasses the [[Andaman and Nicobar Islands]] of [[India]], the [[Mergui Archipelago]] of [[Myanmar]], offshore islands of south-western [[Thailand]], [[Peninsular Malaysia]], southern [[Cambodia]] and [[Vietnam]], and many of the small islands between [[Sumatra]], the [[Philippines]] and the [[Solomon Islands]]. On [[Palau]], the only distinct [[subspecies]] ''C. n. pelewensis'' is found.<ref name=\"grimmettetal1999\" />\n\n[[File:Stavenn Caloenas nicobarica 00.jpg|thumb|left|upright|The white tail is the most conspicuous feature of adult Nicobar pigeons, particularly when seen at a distance in the twilight.]]\nThe Nicobar pigeon roams in flocks from island to island, usually sleeping on offshore islets where no [[predator]]s occur and spends the day in areas with better food availability, not shying away from areas inhabited by humans. Its food consists of [[seed]]s, [[fruit]] and buds, and it is attracted to areas where [[cereal|grain]] is available. A [[gizzard stone]] helps to grind up hard food items. Its flight is quick, with regular beats and an occasional sharp flick of the wings, as is characteristic of pigeons in general. Unlike other pigeons, groups tend to fly in columns or single file, not in a loose flock. The white tail is prominent in flight when seen from behind and may serve as a sort of \"[[taillight]]\", keeping flocks together when crossing the sea at dawn or dusk. The young birds' lack of a white tail is a signal of their immaturity clearly visible to [[conspecific]]s&nbsp;\u2013 to an adult Nicobar pigeon, it is obvious at a glance which flockmembers are neither potential mates, nor potential competitors for mates, nor old enough to safely guide a flock from one island to another.<ref name=\"grimmettetal1999\" />\n\nThis species nests in dense forest on offshore islets, often in large colonies. It builds a loose stick nest in a tree. It lays one elliptical faintly blue-tinged white [[Egg (biology)|egg]].<ref name=\"grimmettetal1999\" />\n\nIn 2017, several individual ''Caloenas nicobarica'' were sighted in the [[Kimberley (Western Australia)|Kimberley]] region of [[Western Australia]] with a juvenile captured at [[Ardyaloon, Western Australia|Ardyaloon]] (One Arm Point), near [[Broome, Western Australia|Broome]] - the first time the bird has been sighted on the Australian mainland.<ref name=Australia>{{cite news| last = Laurie\n| first = Victoria| date = 5 May 2017| title= The dodo's gorgeous island-hopping relative finds its way to our shores| url = http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/health-science/the-dodos-gorgeous-islandhopping-relative-finds-its-way-to-our-shores/news-story/9a62bda7e3d7e4bc69a62aadebf6d63c| work = The Australian| location= Sydney| access-date  = 5 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\n[[File:Taube in Hellabrunn 6613.jpg|thumb|Nicobar pigeon at Munich Zoo Hellabrunn]]\nNicobar pigeons are hunted in considerable numbers for food, and also for their gizzard stone which is used in [[jewellery]]. The species is also trapped for the local [[pet]] market, but as it is on [[CITES Appendix I]], such trade is generally illegal. Internationally, [[captive breeding]] is able to supply the birds demanded by [[zoo]]s, where this attractive and unusual bird is often seen. Direct exploitation of the species, even including the illegal trade, might be sustainable on its own; however, its available nesting [[habitat]] is decreasing. The offshore islets which it requires are often [[logging|logged]] for [[plantation]]s, destroyed by construction activity, or polluted by nearby [[industry]] or [[harbour]]s. Also, increased travel introduces predators to more and more of the breeding sites, and colonies of the Nicobar pigeon may be driven to desert such locations or be destroyed outright. Though the bird is widely distributed and in some locations very common&nbsp;--even on small Palau it is still reasonably plentiful, with an estimated 1,000 adult birds remaining\u2014its long-term future is increasingly jeopardized. For these reasons, the [[IUCN]] considers ''C. nicobarica'' a [[near threatened]] species.<ref>BLI (2009).</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Fuller, Errol (2000): ''Extinct Birds'' (2nd ed.). Oxford University Press, Oxford, New York. {{ISBN|978-0-19-850837-3}}.\n* Grimmett, Richard; Inskipp, Carol, Inskipp, Tim & Byers, Clive (1999): ''Birds of India, Pakistan, Nepal, Bangladesh, Bhutan, Sri Lanka, and the Maldives''. Princeton University Press, Princeton, N.J. {{ISBN|978-0-691-04910-6}}.\n* [[Indian Coast Guard]] (ICG) (2007): [http://www.indiancoastguard.nic.in/Indiancoastguard/RegionNews/A&N%20Region/Sep%2007/Sep%202007.htm Andaman & Nicobar Region News, September 2007]. Retrieved 2009-MAY-22.\n* [[Indian Navy|Integrated Headquarters of Ministry of Defence (Navy)]] (IHMDN) (2005): [http://www.indiannavy.nic.in/in-t19.htm Relief Assistance Provided by Indian Navy&nbsp;\u2013 Update 19 January 05]. Version of 2005-JAN-19. Retrieved 2009-MAY-22.\n* {{cite journal| doi = 10.1006/mpev.1999.0682| last1 = Johnson| first1 = Kevin P.| last2 = Clayton| first2 = Dale H.| year = 2000| title = Nuclear and Mitochondrial Genes Contain Similar Phylogenetic. Signal for Pigeons and Doves (Aves: Columbiformes)| journal = [[Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution]]| volume = 14| issue = 1| pages = 141\u2013151| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20051016131627/http://www.inhs.uiuc.edu/~kjohnson/kpj_pdfs/MPE.Johnson.Clayton.2000.pdf| pmid =  10631048| pmc = | ref = harv\n}}                      <!-- {{sfn|Johnson|Clayton|2000}} -->\n* {{cite journal| doi = 10.1080/10635150701549672| last1 = Pereira | first1 = S. L.| last2 = Johnson | first2 = K. P.| last3 = Clayton | first3 = D. H.| last4 = Baker | first4 = A. J.| year = 2007| title = Mitochondrial and nuclear DNA sequences support a Cretaceous origin of Columbiformes and a dispersal-driven radiation in the Paleogene| journal = Systematic Biology| volume = 56| issue = 4| pages = 656\u2013672| jstor = | pmid = 17661233| pmc = | ref = {{sfnRef|Pereira et al.|2007}} \n}} {{free access}}                  <!-- {{sfn|Pereira et al.|2007}} -->\n* {{cite rowlett|amn|date=2008-10-01|accessdate=2009-05-22}}  <!-- {{sfn|Rowlett|2008}} -->\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Sankaran | first1 = R | year = 1998 | title = An annotated list of the endemic avifauna of the Nicobar islands | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110610175448/http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/13pdfs/Sankaran-Nicobar.pdf | journal = [[Forktail (journal)|Forktail]] | volume = 13 | issue = | pages = 17\u201322 }}\n* {{cite journal| doi = 10.1126/science.295.5560.1683| last1 = Shapiro | first1 = B.| last2 = Sibthorpe | first2 = D.| last3 = Rambaut | first3 = A.| last4 = Austin | first4 = J.| last5 = Wragg | first5 = G. M.| last6 = Bininda-Emonds | first6 = O. R. P.| last7 = Lee | first7 = P. L. M.| last8 = Cooper | first8 = A.| date = 2002| title = Flight of the Dodo| journal = Science| volume = 295| issue = 5560| pages = 1683| jstor = | pmid = 11872833| pmc = | url = http://pgl.soe.ucsc.edu/dodo_Shapiro02.pdf| ref = {{sfnRef|Shapiro et al.|2002}}\n}} [http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/full/295/5560/1683/DC1 Supplementary information] <!-- {{sfn|Shapiro et al.|2002}} -->\n* {{cite journal| doi = 10.1093/molbev/msj124| last1 = Slack| first1 = Kerryn E.| last2 = Jones| first2 = Craig M.| last3 = Ando| first3 = Tatsuro| last4 = Harrison| first4 = G.L. \"Abby| last5 = Fordyce| first5 = R. Ewan| last6 = Arnason| first6 = Ulfur| last7 = Penny| first7 = David| year = 2006| title = Early Penguin Fossils, plus Mitochondrial Genomes, Calibrate Avian Evolution| journal = [[Molecular Biology and Evolution]]| volume = 23| issue = 6| pages = 1144\u20131155| pmid =  16533822| pmc = | url = http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/reprint/23/6/1144| ref = harv\n}}  [http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/full/msj124/DC1 Supplementary Material] {{open access}}       <!-- {{sfn|Slack|Jones|Ando|Harrison|2006}}-->\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Caloenas nicobarica}}\n{{Wikispecies|Caloenas nicobarica}}\n* [http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/nicobar-pigeon-caloenas-nicobarica Nicobar Pigeon media] at the Internet Bird Collection\n\n{{Birds|state=collapsed}}\n{{portalbar|Birds|Animals|Biology}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q605804}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:pigeon, Nicobar}}\n[[Category:Caloenas|Nicobar pigeon]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Andaman and Nicobar Islands]]\n[[Category:Birds of Malesia]]\n[[Category:Birds of Palau]]\n[[Category:Birds of Melanesia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|Nicobar pigeon]]\n", "name_user": "Red dwarf", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicobar_pigeon"}
{"title_page": "Kuk\u00ebs", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement (Albanian)\n| type = m\n| name = Kuk\u00ebs \n| skyline = Bashki_Kukesi.JPG\n| caption = View over the city of Kuk\u00ebs.\n| emblem = Stema_e_Bashkis%C3%AB_Kuk%C3%ABs.svg\n| county = Kuk\u00ebs\n| mayor = [[Safet Gjici]] ([[Socialist Party of Albania|PS]])\n| settled = \n| incorporated =  \n| area_munic = 934.80\n| population_munic = 47985\n| population_unit = 16719\n| population_as_of = 2011\n| demonym = Kuksian/e\n| coordinates = {{coord|42|5|N|20|25|E|type:adm1st_region:AL_dim:100000|display=inline}}\n| elevation = 350\n| postal_code = 8501, 8502, 8503\n| area_code = (0)24 \n| website = {{URL|www.kukesi.gov.al|Official Website}}\n}}\n\n'''Kuk\u00ebs''' ({{lang-sq-definite|Kuk\u00ebsi}}) is a city in the [[Republic of Albania]]. The city is the capital of the surrounding municipality of Kuk\u00ebs and county of [[Kuk\u00ebs County|Kuk\u00ebs]], one of 12 constituent [[Counties of Albania|counties]] of the republic. It spans {{convert|8.2|km\u00b2|sqmi}} and had a total population of 16,719 people as of 2011.<ref name=\"census11\">{{cite web |url=http://www.instat.gov.al/media/3066/8__kukes.pdf |title=Population and housing census - Kuk\u00ebs 2011 |accessdate=2019-09-25 |publisher=[[Institute of Statistics (Albania)|INSTAT]] }}</ref><ref name=\"GeographyKuk\u00ebs\"/> By air distance, Kuk\u00ebs is located {{convert|98|km}} northeast of [[Tirana]], {{convert|75|km}} to the east of [[Shkod\u00ebr]] and {{convert|34|km}} to the south of [[Gjakov\u00eb]] and {{convert|30|km}} to the west of [[Prizren]] in [[Kosovo]].\n\n[[Geologically]], the terrain of the surrounding area is dominated by mountainous and high terrain. The city sprawls across the [[Lum\u00eb (region)|Luma Plain]] within the [[Albanian Alps]] between the banks of [[Lake Fierza]] and the hills of the northernmost [[Korab|Korab Mountains]] and westernmost [[Shar Mountains]]. At the confluence of the [[Black Drin|Black]] and [[White Drin]], the [[Drin (river)|Drin River]] originates close to the city's territory.\n\nKuk\u00ebs traces its history back over a thousand years. The region that nowadays corresponds to the city territory was inhabited by several ancient [[Illyrian tribe]]s, as most of Albania. Numerous tombs from the [[Illyrians]] has been identified at K\u00ebneta and [[Kolsh, Kuk\u00ebs|Kolsh]] nearby the city. The residential estate served as a stopping point on a branch road leading to the [[Via Egnatia]], which connected [[Durr\u00ebs]] on the [[Adriatic Sea]] in the west with [[Constantinople]] on the [[Sea of Marmara|Marmara Sea]] in the east. In [[Contemporary history|modern time]]s and due to the close proximity to Kosovo, the city achieved worldwide recognition during the [[Kosovo War]] as thousands of [[Kosovo Albanians|Kosovo-Albanian]] refugees crossed the border and found security in the city.\n\nThe city was nominated for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] in regard to hospitality and for embracing thousands of refugees during the Kosovo War.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kuk\u00ebsi, kryeqendra shqiptare m\u00eb 16 prill|url=http://gazeta-shqip.com/lajme/2014/04/16/kukesi-kryeqendra-shqiptare-16-prill-2/|website=gazeta-shqip.com|accessdate=16 April 2014|page=1|language=Albanian}}</ref> It was the first time a town was nominated for the prize. In 2017, the city applied for the 2018 [[European Green Capital Award]] to become [[Europe]]'s Green Capital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/environment/europeangreencapital/news/20161116.html|title=European Green Capital|website=ec.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2017-08-27}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe old Kuk\u00ebs was located at the confluence of the [[White Drin]] and [[Black Drin]]. In 1976 the town was submerged beneath the [[Fierza Reservoir]], which is held back by a [[dam]]. \nThe new town (''Kuk\u00ebsi i Ri'' - \"New Kuk\u00ebs\") was built in the 1970s in the plateau nearby which is 320m over the sea level. Kuk\u00ebsi i Ri is surrounded by the artificial lake of Fierza and it looks like a peninsula from the above. \nIt is linked with the other parts of the country by three bridges. On the east it faces the snow-covered mountain of Gjallica, 2468&nbsp;m above sea level. \n\n[[Illyrians|Illyrian]] tombs were found at K\u00ebneta and [[Kolsh, Kuk\u00ebs|Kolsh]] nearby Kuk\u00ebs.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boardman, Edwards|first1=John ,I. E. S.|title=The Cambridge Ancient History|date=1982|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=235|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vXljf8JqmkoC&pg=PA235&lpg=PA235&dq=kukes+illyrian+tombs&source=bl&ots=QxogesxpQr&sig=EnDnDIEXFGXSknT8-01bbr0EIko&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiNxuvgmaDKAhVDOg8KHRXVBU8Q6AEIPjAH#v=onepage&q=kukes%20illyrian%20tombs&f=false|accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref> It was a small Roman settlement, a stopping point on a branch road leading to the [[Via Egnatia]], and a minor Ottoman market centre and trading post on the road to southern Kosovo.{{efn|name=status}} It was there (Qafa e Kolosjanit) where Albanian resistance stood up against retreating Serbian army in 1912.\n\nKuk\u00ebs attracted international attention during the [[Kosovo conflict]] when 450,000 Kosovo Albanian [[refugee]]s crossed the frontier and were housed in camps in and around Kuk\u00ebs.\nThis led, in 2000, to a nomination for the Nobel Peace Prize. It was the first time a town was nominated for the prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/KOSOVO-KUKES-NOMINATED-FOR-NOBEL-PEACE-PRIZE/fc9502cfaf30caf4c1dd1bebdc2f29af?query=MIDDLE+EAST&current=18&orderBy=Relevance&hits=36&referrer=search&search=/search?query=MIDDLE%2520EAST&startd=&endd=&orderBy=Relevance&from=1&allFilters=KOSOVO%253AKeyword%252CSocial+affairs%253ASubject%252CEnvironment+and+nature%253ASubject%252CREFUGEES%253AKeyword&allFilters=KOSOVO:Keyword,Social+affairs:Subject,Environment+and+nature:Subject,REFUGEES:Keyword&productType=IncludedProducts&page=1&b=2f29af|title=KOSOVO: KUKES NOMINATED FOR NOBEL PEACE PRIZE {{!}} AP Archive|website=www.aparchive.com|access-date=2017-08-27}}</ref>\n\nThere is a [[mosque]] and a closed alpine-style [[hotel]], part of an attempt to establish a [[tourist industry]] there. [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe|OSCE]] maintained a villa there.\n\n== Environment ==\n\nKuk\u00ebs is situated in the northeast of the country. It lies mostly between [[latitude]]s 42\u00b0 and 5\u00b0 N, and [[longitude]]s 20\u00b0 and 25\u00b0 E. The city extend strategically within the [[Albanian Alps]] and is trapped on four sides by numerous [[two-thousander]]s including [[Gjallica]] in the south, [[Koritnik]] in the east, [[Pashtrik]] in the northeast and several mountains in the west. It lies on the Luma Plain and the southern shores of [[Lake Fierza]].<ref name=\"GeographyKuk\u00ebs\">{{cite web|author1=Bashkia Kuk\u00ebs|title=PLANI I ZHVILLIMIT I BASHKISE KUKES|url=http://www.rasp.org.al/assets/pzhkukes.pdf|website=rasp.org.al|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014034014/http://www.rasp.org.al/assets/pzhkukes.pdf|archivedate=14 October 2017|location=Kuk\u00ebs|language=Albanian|format=PDF}}</ref> It lies approximately {{convert|3|km|mi}} in the southeast of the former location of the city, which was relocated as part of a [[Fierza Hydroelectric Power Station|hydroelectric]] scheme.<ref name=\"GeographyKuk\u00ebs\"/>\n\n=== Climate ===\nLike all East Albanians who are in the plain the zone is [[Humid subtropical climate|humid subtropical]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: ''Cfa''), similar to the north of [[Italy]], due to its interior location but near the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. Despite its southern location, its distance to the east compensates for this difference.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.climate-data.org/europe/albania/kukes/kukes-46032/|title=Kuk\u00ebs climate: Average Temperature, weather by month, Kuk\u00ebs weather averages - Climate-Data.org|website=en.climate-data.org|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Peterson|first=Adam|title=English: K\u00f6ppen climate types of Albania|date=2016-11-02|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Albania_K%C3%B6ppen.svg|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> The climate of the city is profoundly impacted by the [[Albanian Alps]] in the northeast, [[Shar Mountains]] in the east, [[Korab|Korab Mountains]] in the southeast and the [[Drin (river)|Drin River]] in the south. The city experiences mostly [[Continental climate|continental]] climate.<ref name=\"GeographyKuk\u00ebs\"/><ref>{{cite web|author1=Bashkia Kuk\u00ebs|title=Programi i Zon\u00ebs Funksionale Kuk\u00ebs|url=http://www.km.dldp.al/wp-multimedia/fap/covera/Shqip/PZF%20Kukes.pdf|website=km.dldp.al|location=Kuk\u00ebs|pages=11\u201312|language=Albanian|format=PDF}}</ref> This means that the winters are very cold and snowy and the summers are predominantly hot. The city's temperature varies a large deal across the seasons with a mild spring in April and May, hot summer months from June to August, frequently rainy and windy autumn months in September and October and very cold winter months, often with snow and frost, from December to March. The mean monthly [[temperature]] ranges between {{convert|-25|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|lk=on}}{{Dubious|date=May 2019}} in winter and {{convert|25|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|lk=off}} in summer.<ref name=\"GeographyKuk\u00ebs\"/> The mean annual [[precipitation]] ranges between {{convert|900|mm|in|abbr=off}} and {{convert|3000|mm|in|abbr=off}} depending on [[longitude]] and [[latitude]].<ref name=\"GeographyKuk\u00ebs\"/>{{Weather box    \n| width        = 100% <!-- 77% if there is a template or image next to it -->\n| collapsed    = <!-- y, if you have normal updates -->\n| open         = \n| metric first = y <!-- always, except UK or US cities -->\n| single line  = y\n| location     = Kuk\u00ebs, elevation: {{convert|44|m|abbr=on|disp=or}}, 1961-1990 normals and extremes{{efn|Monthly data only for temperatures}}\n<!--in the order as it appears in the table, not all of the following data may be available, especially records and days of precipitation -->\n|year mean C =12.3      \n| Jan high C  =3.8    \n| Feb high C  =7.2    \n| Mar high C  =12.1     \n| Apr high C  =17.4     \n| May high C  =22.5    \n| Jun high C  =25.9    \n| Jul high C  =28.8    \n| Aug high C  =28.8    \n| Sep high C  =24.6    \n| Oct high C  =18.1     \n| Nov high C  =11.3     \n| Dec high C  =5.6    \n| Jan low C  =-2.9\n| Feb low C  =-1.2\n| Mar low C  =1.8\n| Apr low C  =6.2\n| May low C  =10.8\n| Jun low C  =14.0\n| Jul low C  =15.6\n| Aug low C  =15.2\n| Sep low C  =11.9\n| Oct low C  =7.0\n| Nov low C  =3.1\n| Dec low C  =-0.8\n| Jan record high C =19.7   \n| Feb record high C =23.1   \n| Mar record high C =26.9   \n| Apr record high C =30.6    \n| May record high C =35.0     \n| Jun record high C =39.2     \n| Jul record high C =40.2     \n| Aug record high C =38.7     \n| Sep record high C =35.4     \n| Oct record high C =30.6    \n| Nov record high C =25.4   \n| Dec record high C =22.0   \n| Jan record low C  =-22.0\n| Feb record low C  =-14.5\n| Mar record low C  =-13.0\n| Apr record low C  =-2.8\n| May record low C  =0.5      \n| Jun record low C  =4.0      \n| Jul record low C  =6.9      \n| Aug record low C  =6.4      \n| Sep record low C  =0.0      \n| Oct record low C  =-3.0      \n| Nov record low C  =-16.0\n| Dec record low C  =-16.3   \n| precipitation colour  = green\n| Jan precipitation mm  = na\n|year precipitation mm = 909.8\n| Jan humidity    = na \n| year humidity   = 66.0\n| Jan sun  = na\n| year sun = 1973.1\n| unit rain days = 1.0 mm\n| Jan rain days  = na\n| year rain days = 95.0\n| Jan snow days  = na\n| year snow days = 17.0\n| source = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]]<ref name = noaa>{{cite web\n| url = ftp://ftp.atdd.noaa.gov/pub/GCOS/WMO-Normals/TABLES/REG_VI/AB/13610.TXT\n| title = Kuk\u00ebs (13610) - WMO Weather Station\n| accessdate = August 28, 2019\n| publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Politics==\n\nThe Kuk\u00ebs municipality was formed in 2015 by the merger of the former municipalities [[Arr\u00ebn]], [[Bicaj]], [[Bushtric\u00eb]], [[Gryk\u00eb-\u00c7aj\u00eb]], [[Kalis, Albania|Kalis]], [[Kolsh, Kuk\u00ebs|Kolsh]], Kuk\u00ebs, [[Malzi]], [[Shishtavec (administrative unit)|Shishtavec]], [[Shtiq\u00ebn]], [[Surroj]], [[T\u00ebrthore]], [[Topojan]], [[Ujmisht]] and [[Zapod]], that became municipal units.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf|title=FLETORJA ZYRTARE E REPUBLIK\u00cbS S\u00cb SHQIP\u00cbRIS\u00cb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085559/http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> The municipality spans {{convert|934.80|km\u00b2|sqmi}} and had a total population of 47,985 people as of 2011.<ref name=\"LAU\">{{cite web |url=https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/345175/501971/EU-28-LAU-2019-NUTS-2016.xlsx |title=Correspondence table LAU \u2013 NUTS 2016, EU-28 and EFTA / available Candidate Countries |accessdate=2019-09-25 |publisher=[[Eurostat]]|format=XLS }}</ref><ref name=\"census11\" />\n\n== Economy ==\n \nThere is also a local historical museum and a carpet factory. \nThe food industry is confined only to production of alcoholic drinks produced in a drink factory, and to some local small workshops producing drinks and dairy products.\n\nThe Highlanders in the region are well known for their developed agriculture. Kuk\u00ebs has a carpet factory whose products is for domestic and trade use. There is also a copper processing factory as the raw material, copper, is found in this place. \nKuk\u00ebs is a good centre for fishing and walking in the surrounding mountains.\n\nKuk\u00ebs has an [[Kuk\u00ebs International Airport Shaikh Zayed|international airport]] of its own. It is located approximately about 3.5&nbsp;km (2.2&nbsp;mi) south of Kuk\u00ebs city centre. The government of Albania granted permission for it to host international passenger traffic in 2016. Low-cost companies like the Irish [[Ryan Air]] and the Hungarian [[Wizz Air]], as well the Slovenian [[Adria Airways]] have expressed their interest in operating from the [[Kuk\u00ebs International Airport Shaikh Zayed|Kuk\u00ebs International Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oranews.tv/ora-english/kukes-airport-hungarian-company-wizz-air-showing-interest-in-the-airport/|title=Oranews.tv - Kukes airport, hungarian company Wizz Air showing interest in the airport|website=Oranews|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828020806/http://www.oranews.tv/ora-english/kukes-airport-hungarian-company-wizz-air-showing-interest-in-the-airport/|archivedate=2017-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://seenews.com/news/wizz-air-adria-airways-ryanair-eye-flights-from-albanias-kukes-report-538741|title=Wizz Air, Adria Airways, Ryanair eye flights from Albania's Kukes - report|website=seenews.com|language=en|access-date=2017-08-27}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Albania-Kosovo Highway|A1]] highway passes through Kuk\u00ebs.\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Dritan Hoxha]]  -  Albanian businessman\n* [[Safet Gjici]]  -  Albanian businessman\n* [[Rrahman Halla\u00e7i]]  -  professional football coach\n* [[Zehrudin Dokle]]  -  actor\n* [[Hersi Matmuja]]  -   Albanian singer\n\n==Sister cities==\n* {{flagicon|Albania}} '''[[Sh\u00ebngjin]]''', [[Albania]]\n* {{flagicon|Kosovo}}  '''[[Prizren]]''', [[Kosovo]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} '''[[Lyndhurst, New Jersey|Lyndhurst]]''', [[United States]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of mayors of Kuk\u00ebs]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notes\n| notes =\n{{efn\n| name = status\n| {{Kosovo-note}}\n}}\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = <span style=\"vertical-align: 1px;\">[[File:Coat_of_arms_of_Albania.svg|20x20px]]</span> <span style=\"color:#00006e;\">Topics related to Kuk\u00ebs </span>\n| titlestyle = color:black; background-color:white;\n|list1=\n{{Municipalities of Albania}}\n{{Kuk\u00ebs County}}\n{{Kuk\u00ebs div}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kukes}}\n[[Category:Kuk\u00ebs| ]]\n[[Category:Kuk\u00ebs County| ]]\n[[Category:Municipalities in Kuk\u00ebs County]]\n[[Category:Administrative units of Kuk\u00ebs]]\n[[Category:Towns in Albania]]\n[[Category:Geg\u00ebri]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement (Albanian)\n| type = m\n| name = Kuk\u00ebs \n| skyline = Bashki_Kukesi.JPG\n| caption = View over the city of Kuk\u00ebs.\n| emblem = Stema_e_Bashkis%C3%AB_Kuk%C3%ABs.svg\n| county = [[Kuk\u00ebs County]]\n| mayor = [[Safet Gjici]] ([[Socialist Party of Albania|PS]])\n| settled = \n| incorporated =  \n| area_munic = 934.80\n| population_munic = 47985\n| population_unit = 16719\n| population_as_of = 2011\n| demonym = Kuksian/e\n| coordinates = {{coord|42|5|N|20|25|E|type:adm1st_region:AL_dim:100000|display=inline}}\n| elevation = 350\n| postal_code = 8501, 8502, 8503\n| area_code = (0)24 \n| website = {{URL|www.kukesi.gov.al|Official Website}}\n}}\n\n'''Kuk\u00ebs''' ({{lang-sq-definite|Kuk\u00ebsi}}) is a city in the [[Republic of Albania]]. The city is the capital of the surrounding municipality of Kuk\u00ebs and county of [[Kuk\u00ebs County|Kuk\u00ebs]], one of 12 constituent [[Counties of Albania|counties]] of the republic. It spans {{convert|8.2|km\u00b2|sqmi}} and had a total population of 16,719 people as of 2011.<ref name=\"census11\">{{cite web |url=http://www.instat.gov.al/media/3066/8__kukes.pdf |title=Population and housing census - Kuk\u00ebs 2011 |accessdate=2019-09-25 |publisher=[[Institute of Statistics (Albania)|INSTAT]] }}</ref><ref name=\"GeographyKuk\u00ebs\"/> By air distance, Kuk\u00ebs is located {{convert|98|km}} northeast of [[Tirana]], {{convert|75|km}} to the east of [[Shkod\u00ebr]] and {{convert|34|km}} to the south of [[Gjakov\u00eb]] and {{convert|30|km}} to the west of [[Prizren]] in [[Kosovo]].\n\n[[Geologically]], the terrain of the surrounding area is dominated by mountainous and high terrain. The city sprawls across the [[Lum\u00eb (region)|Luma Plain]] within the [[Albanian Alps]] between the banks of [[Lake Fierza]] and the hills of the northernmost [[Korab|Korab Mountains]] and westernmost [[Shar Mountains]]. At the confluence of the [[Black Drin|Black]] and [[White Drin]], the [[Drin (river)|Drin River]] originates close to the city's territory.\n\nKuk\u00ebs traces its history back over a thousand years. The region that nowadays corresponds to the city territory was inhabited by several ancient [[Illyrian tribe]]s, as most of Albania. Numerous tombs from the [[Illyrians]] has been identified at K\u00ebneta and [[Kolsh, Kuk\u00ebs|Kolsh]] nearby the city. The residential estate served as a stopping point on a branch road leading to the [[Via Egnatia]], which connected [[Durr\u00ebs]] on the [[Adriatic Sea]] in the west with [[Constantinople]] on the [[Sea of Marmara|Marmara Sea]] in the east. In [[Contemporary history|modern time]]s and due to the close proximity to Kosovo, the city achieved worldwide recognition during the [[Kosovo War]] as thousands of [[Kosovo Albanians|Kosovo-Albanian]] refugees crossed the border and found security in the city.\n\nThe city was nominated for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] in regard to hospitality and for embracing thousands of refugees during the Kosovo War.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kuk\u00ebsi, kryeqendra shqiptare m\u00eb 16 prill|url=http://gazeta-shqip.com/lajme/2014/04/16/kukesi-kryeqendra-shqiptare-16-prill-2/|website=gazeta-shqip.com|accessdate=16 April 2014|page=1|language=Albanian}}</ref> It was the first time a town was nominated for the prize. In 2017, the city applied for the 2018 [[European Green Capital Award]] to become [[Europe]]'s Green Capital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/environment/europeangreencapital/news/20161116.html|title=European Green Capital|website=ec.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2017-08-27}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe old Kuk\u00ebs was located at the confluence of the [[White Drin]] and [[Black Drin]]. In 1976 the town was submerged beneath the [[Fierza Reservoir]], which is held back by a [[dam]]. \nThe new town (''Kuk\u00ebsi i Ri'' - \"New Kuk\u00ebs\") was built in the 1970s in the plateau nearby which is 320m over the sea level. Kuk\u00ebsi i Ri is surrounded by the artificial lake of Fierza and it looks like a peninsula from the above. \nIt is linked with the other parts of the country by three bridges. On the east it faces the snow-covered mountain of Gjallica, 2468&nbsp;m above sea level. \n\n[[Illyrians|Illyrian]] tombs were found at K\u00ebneta and [[Kolsh, Kuk\u00ebs|Kolsh]] nearby Kuk\u00ebs.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boardman, Edwards|first1=John ,I. E. S.|title=The Cambridge Ancient History|date=1982|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=235|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vXljf8JqmkoC&pg=PA235&lpg=PA235&dq=kukes+illyrian+tombs&source=bl&ots=QxogesxpQr&sig=EnDnDIEXFGXSknT8-01bbr0EIko&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiNxuvgmaDKAhVDOg8KHRXVBU8Q6AEIPjAH#v=onepage&q=kukes%20illyrian%20tombs&f=false|accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref> It was a small Roman settlement, a stopping point on a branch road leading to the [[Via Egnatia]], and a minor Ottoman market centre and trading post on the road to southern Kosovo.{{efn|name=status}} It was there (Qafa e Kolosjanit) where Albanian resistance stood up against retreating Serbian army in 1912.\n\nKuk\u00ebs attracted international attention during the [[Kosovo conflict]] when 450,000 Kosovo Albanian [[refugee]]s crossed the frontier and were housed in camps in and around Kuk\u00ebs.\nThis led, in 2000, to a nomination for the Nobel Peace Prize. It was the first time a town was nominated for the prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/KOSOVO-KUKES-NOMINATED-FOR-NOBEL-PEACE-PRIZE/fc9502cfaf30caf4c1dd1bebdc2f29af?query=MIDDLE+EAST&current=18&orderBy=Relevance&hits=36&referrer=search&search=/search?query=MIDDLE%2520EAST&startd=&endd=&orderBy=Relevance&from=1&allFilters=KOSOVO%253AKeyword%252CSocial+affairs%253ASubject%252CEnvironment+and+nature%253ASubject%252CREFUGEES%253AKeyword&allFilters=KOSOVO:Keyword,Social+affairs:Subject,Environment+and+nature:Subject,REFUGEES:Keyword&productType=IncludedProducts&page=1&b=2f29af|title=KOSOVO: KUKES NOMINATED FOR NOBEL PEACE PRIZE {{!}} AP Archive|website=www.aparchive.com|access-date=2017-08-27}}</ref>\n\nThere is a [[mosque]] and a closed alpine-style [[hotel]], part of an attempt to establish a [[tourist industry]] there. [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe|OSCE]] maintained a villa there.\n\n== Environment ==\n\nKuk\u00ebs is situated in the northeast of the country. It lies mostly between [[latitude]]s 42\u00b0 and 5\u00b0 N, and [[longitude]]s 20\u00b0 and 25\u00b0 E. The city extend strategically within the [[Albanian Alps]] and is trapped on four sides by numerous [[two-thousander]]s including [[Gjallica]] in the south, [[Koritnik]] in the east, [[Pashtrik]] in the northeast and several mountains in the west. It lies on the Luma Plain and the southern shores of [[Lake Fierza]].<ref name=\"GeographyKuk\u00ebs\">{{cite web|author1=Bashkia Kuk\u00ebs|title=PLANI I ZHVILLIMIT I BASHKISE KUKES|url=http://www.rasp.org.al/assets/pzhkukes.pdf|website=rasp.org.al|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014034014/http://www.rasp.org.al/assets/pzhkukes.pdf|archivedate=14 October 2017|location=Kuk\u00ebs|language=Albanian|format=PDF}}</ref> It lies approximately {{convert|3|km|mi}} in the southeast of the former location of the city, which was relocated as part of a [[Fierza Hydroelectric Power Station|hydroelectric]] scheme.<ref name=\"GeographyKuk\u00ebs\"/>\n\n=== Climate ===\nLike all East Albanians who are in the plain the zone is [[Humid subtropical climate|humid subtropical]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: ''Cfa''), similar to the north of [[Italy]], due to its interior location but near the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. Despite its southern location, its distance to the east compensates for this difference.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.climate-data.org/europe/albania/kukes/kukes-46032/|title=Kuk\u00ebs climate: Average Temperature, weather by month, Kuk\u00ebs weather averages - Climate-Data.org|website=en.climate-data.org|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Peterson|first=Adam|title=English: K\u00f6ppen climate types of Albania|date=2016-11-02|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Albania_K%C3%B6ppen.svg|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> The climate of the city is profoundly impacted by the [[Albanian Alps]] in the northeast, [[Shar Mountains]] in the east, [[Korab|Korab Mountains]] in the southeast and the [[Drin (river)|Drin River]] in the south. The city experiences mostly [[Continental climate|continental]] climate.<ref name=\"GeographyKuk\u00ebs\"/><ref>{{cite web|author1=Bashkia Kuk\u00ebs|title=Programi i Zon\u00ebs Funksionale Kuk\u00ebs|url=http://www.km.dldp.al/wp-multimedia/fap/covera/Shqip/PZF%20Kukes.pdf|website=km.dldp.al|location=Kuk\u00ebs|pages=11\u201312|language=Albanian|format=PDF}}</ref> This means that the winters are very cold and snowy and the summers are predominantly hot. The city's temperature varies a large deal across the seasons with a mild spring in April and May, hot summer months from June to August, frequently rainy and windy autumn months in September and October and very cold winter months, often with snow and frost, from December to March. The mean monthly [[temperature]] ranges between {{convert|-25|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|lk=on}}{{Dubious|date=May 2019}} in winter and {{convert|25|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|lk=off}} in summer.<ref name=\"GeographyKuk\u00ebs\"/> The mean annual [[precipitation]] ranges between {{convert|900|mm|in|abbr=off}} and {{convert|3000|mm|in|abbr=off}} depending on [[longitude]] and [[latitude]].<ref name=\"GeographyKuk\u00ebs\"/>{{Weather box    \n| width        = 100% <!-- 77% if there is a template or image next to it -->\n| collapsed    = <!-- y, if you have normal updates -->\n| open         = \n| metric first = y <!-- always, except UK or US cities -->\n| single line  = y\n| location     = Kuk\u00ebs, elevation: {{convert|44|m|abbr=on|disp=or}}, 1961-1990 normals and extremes{{efn|Monthly data only for temperatures}}\n<!--in the order as it appears in the table, not all of the following data may be available, especially records and days of precipitation -->\n|year mean C =12.3      \n| Jan high C  =3.8    \n| Feb high C  =7.2    \n| Mar high C  =12.1     \n| Apr high C  =17.4     \n| May high C  =22.5    \n| Jun high C  =25.9    \n| Jul high C  =28.8    \n| Aug high C  =28.8    \n| Sep high C  =24.6    \n| Oct high C  =18.1     \n| Nov high C  =11.3     \n| Dec high C  =5.6    \n| Jan low C  =-2.9\n| Feb low C  =-1.2\n| Mar low C  =1.8\n| Apr low C  =6.2\n| May low C  =10.8\n| Jun low C  =14.0\n| Jul low C  =15.6\n| Aug low C  =15.2\n| Sep low C  =11.9\n| Oct low C  =7.0\n| Nov low C  =3.1\n| Dec low C  =-0.8\n| Jan record high C =19.7   \n| Feb record high C =23.1   \n| Mar record high C =26.9   \n| Apr record high C =30.6    \n| May record high C =35.0     \n| Jun record high C =39.2     \n| Jul record high C =40.2     \n| Aug record high C =38.7     \n| Sep record high C =35.4     \n| Oct record high C =30.6    \n| Nov record high C =25.4   \n| Dec record high C =22.0   \n| Jan record low C  =-22.0\n| Feb record low C  =-14.5\n| Mar record low C  =-13.0\n| Apr record low C  =-2.8\n| May record low C  =0.5      \n| Jun record low C  =4.0      \n| Jul record low C  =6.9      \n| Aug record low C  =6.4      \n| Sep record low C  =0.0      \n| Oct record low C  =-3.0      \n| Nov record low C  =-16.0\n| Dec record low C  =-16.3   \n| precipitation colour  = green\n| Jan precipitation mm  = na\n|year precipitation mm = 909.8\n| Jan humidity    = na \n| year humidity   = 66.0\n| Jan sun  = na\n| year sun = 1973.1\n| unit rain days = 1.0 mm\n| Jan rain days  = na\n| year rain days = 95.0\n| Jan snow days  = na\n| year snow days = 17.0\n| source = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]]<ref name = noaa>{{cite web\n| url = ftp://ftp.atdd.noaa.gov/pub/GCOS/WMO-Normals/TABLES/REG_VI/AB/13610.TXT\n| title = Kuk\u00ebs (13610) - WMO Weather Station\n| accessdate = August 28, 2019\n| publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Politics==\n\nThe Kuk\u00ebs municipality was formed in 2015 by the merger of the former municipalities [[Arr\u00ebn]], [[Bicaj]], [[Bushtric\u00eb]], [[Gryk\u00eb-\u00c7aj\u00eb]], [[Kalis, Albania|Kalis]], [[Kolsh, Kuk\u00ebs|Kolsh]], Kuk\u00ebs, [[Malzi]], [[Shishtavec (administrative unit)|Shishtavec]], [[Shtiq\u00ebn]], [[Surroj]], [[T\u00ebrthore]], [[Topojan]], [[Ujmisht]] and [[Zapod]], that became municipal units.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf|title=FLETORJA ZYRTARE E REPUBLIK\u00cbS S\u00cb SHQIP\u00cbRIS\u00cb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085559/http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> The municipality spans {{convert|934.80|km\u00b2|sqmi}} and had a total population of 47,985 people as of 2011.<ref name=\"LAU\">{{cite web |url=https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/345175/501971/EU-28-LAU-2019-NUTS-2016.xlsx |title=Correspondence table LAU \u2013 NUTS 2016, EU-28 and EFTA / available Candidate Countries |accessdate=2019-09-25 |publisher=[[Eurostat]]|format=XLS }}</ref><ref name=\"census11\" />\n\n== Economy ==\n \nThere is also a local historical museum and a carpet factory. \nThe food industry is confined only to production of alcoholic drinks produced in a drink factory, and to some local small workshops producing drinks and dairy products.\n\nThe Highlanders in the region are well known for their developed agriculture. Kuk\u00ebs has a carpet factory whose products is for domestic and trade use. There is also a copper processing factory as the raw material, copper, is found in this place. \nKuk\u00ebs is a good centre for fishing and walking in the surrounding mountains.\n\nKuk\u00ebs has an [[Kuk\u00ebs International Airport Shaikh Zayed|international airport]] of its own. It is located approximately about 3.5&nbsp;km (2.2&nbsp;mi) south of Kuk\u00ebs city centre. The government of Albania granted permission for it to host international passenger traffic in 2016. Low-cost companies like the Irish [[Ryan Air]] and the Hungarian [[Wizz Air]], as well the Slovenian [[Adria Airways]] have expressed their interest in operating from the [[Kuk\u00ebs International Airport Shaikh Zayed|Kuk\u00ebs International Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oranews.tv/ora-english/kukes-airport-hungarian-company-wizz-air-showing-interest-in-the-airport/|title=Oranews.tv - Kukes airport, hungarian company Wizz Air showing interest in the airport|website=Oranews|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828020806/http://www.oranews.tv/ora-english/kukes-airport-hungarian-company-wizz-air-showing-interest-in-the-airport/|archivedate=2017-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://seenews.com/news/wizz-air-adria-airways-ryanair-eye-flights-from-albanias-kukes-report-538741|title=Wizz Air, Adria Airways, Ryanair eye flights from Albania's Kukes - report|website=seenews.com|language=en|access-date=2017-08-27}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Albania-Kosovo Highway|A1]] highway passes through Kuk\u00ebs.\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Dritan Hoxha]]  -  Albanian businessman\n* [[Safet Gjici]]  -  Albanian businessman\n* [[Rrahman Halla\u00e7i]]  -  professional football coach\n* [[Zehrudin Dokle]]  -  actor\n* [[Hersi Matmuja]]  -   Albanian singer\n\n==Sister cities==\n* {{flagicon|Albania}} '''[[Sh\u00ebngjin]]''', [[Albania]]\n* {{flagicon|Kosovo}}  '''[[Prizren]]''', [[Kosovo]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} '''[[Lyndhurst, New Jersey|Lyndhurst]]''', [[United States]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of mayors of Kuk\u00ebs]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notes\n| notes =\n{{efn\n| name = status\n| {{Kosovo-note}}\n}}\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = <span style=\"vertical-align: 1px;\">[[File:Coat_of_arms_of_Albania.svg|20x20px]]</span> <span style=\"color:#00006e;\">Topics related to Kuk\u00ebs </span>\n| titlestyle = color:black; background-color:white;\n|list1=\n{{Municipalities of Albania}}\n{{Kuk\u00ebs County}}\n{{Kuk\u00ebs div}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kukes}}\n[[Category:Kuk\u00ebs| ]]\n[[Category:Kuk\u00ebs County| ]]\n[[Category:Municipalities in Kuk\u00ebs County]]\n[[Category:Administrative units of Kuk\u00ebs]]\n[[Category:Towns in Albania]]\n[[Category:Geg\u00ebri]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kuk%C3%ABs"}
